<section class="py-20 px-6 bg-gray-900/50 border-y border-gray-800">
  <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto space-y-12">
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold">The Problem</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-400 text-lg">
        Large agent Markdown files are hard to maintain in distributed teams.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <p class="text-gray-300">
          When multiple developers edit the same <code class="bg-gray-800 px-2 py-1 rounded text-brand-400">CLAUDE.md</code> or <code class="bg-gray-800 px-2 py-1 rounded text-brand-400">AGENTS.md</code> file, you hit merge conflicts. But these aren't simple syntactic conflicts — they're semantic.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300">
          Resolving conflicts requires understanding the instruction logic, which is slow and error-prone.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto font-mono text-sm">
        <pre class="text-gray-300"><code>&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt; HEAD
Your role is to be
a senior architect.
=======
You are a Python
code reviewer.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
